Munich 1856: Four maps that change your view of the city
It's a crazy place where young people are supposed to meet today.
A tomb chapel, where now is dug for the S-Bahn tunnel.
Small gardeners cultivate the former ground of farmers.
The oldest official map in Munich brings out exciting stories.
It sucks when maps are not up to date.
Anyone who had to get upset before, because the Auto-Navi displayed a green meadow instead of a bypass.
The historical maps of the digital Bavaria Atlas, an offer from the Bavarian Geoportal of the state government, are anything but up-to-date - but that is precisely why it is very enlightening.
Especially if you compare them with current online cards.
Then it becomes clear how cities and communities in the distribution area of the Munich Mercury have changed since the 19th century.
The digital Bavaria Atlas is a patchwork carpet that is not recognized as such.
More detailed maps, so-called Urpositionsblatten, were incorporated into the large overview map for cities and municipalities.
According to the Bavarian survey administration, these were created between 1810 and 1864 and originate from the first survey of Bavaria.
Your client: Napoleon.
The French army leader occupied Bavaria with Austria since the spring of 1800 during the Second Coalition War.
Napoleon wanted an overview of the occupied country and commissioned a topographical photograph of Bavaria - of course for military purposes.
Even though the French troops finally withdrew with the Peace of Lunéville of 9 February 1801: It was today's neighbors who created the idea of a comprehensive map of Bavaria.
Elector Max IV Joseph continued to advance the project, founded the "Topographic Bureau" - and thus the Bavarian Surveying Administration.
The Urpositionsblatt for Munich dates back to 1856 and can be found on the website of the Bayerische Landesbibliothek, like all others.
The comparison earlier/today is most impressive in the case of the state capital.
The city has expanded in all directions and has grown together.
An example of this is Untersendling, which appears relatively isolated in the map of 1856.
Sendling was incorporated as a Münchner borough 21 years after the map was created, i.e. 1877.
Today Untersendling is located in the middle of the city.
The houses of Untersendlings are concentrated around 1856 along the present-day Plinganserstraße, which was only named in 1878 after Georg Sebastian Plinganser, a leader of the Bavarian peasants' uprising against Austria in 1705.
Where the Westpark is today, you can see nothing but fields - at first glance: When zooming in, a smaller map with dozens of lines and numbers appears: hand-written numbered hallway pieces from the so-called "original image", from which the property tax was derived.
Small plots now no longer occupy farmers there - but small gardeners of the plant "Land in Sonne".
A large green area stands out north of Untersendling.
The Theresienwiese, since 1810 the scene of the Oktoberfest, was in fact still a meadow - and not a concrete desert.
On the other side of the Isar, the historical map gives an insight into the history of psychiatric medicine.
In the Urpositionsblatt one reads in the area of the present district Au-Haidhausen not only the street name "am Gasteig" or from the hill "On the air" - but also in large letters "Irren Anstalt".
Yes, here on Auerfeldstraße, people with delusions were once locked up.
There the Munich Kreis-Irrenanstalt "Auf der Auer Lüften" was founded in 1858/59.
From 1872 Dr. Bernhard von Gudden led the institution - that psychiatrist who was brought in connection with the death of King Louis II.
"He was progressive for his time and ended, for example, the chaining of the so-called madmen.
He also prohibited the staff from using violence against the inmates," says Hermann Wilhelm, head of the Haidhausen Museum, who worked with the institution for an exhibition.
For 280 patients there had initially been space, later being extended to 500 places.
At some point this capacity was no longer sufficient - the reason for the construction of the Kreisirrenanstalt in Haar 1905.
Since 2006, the Isar-Amper-Klinikum München-Ost has been located there, one of the largest psychiatry in Germany.
On the site of the former Auer Anstalt, young people are now meeting in the Munich Salesianum.
The Order acquired the building complex in 1920 and converted it into a youth home with educational establishments.
West is the football field of the TSV Munich East, east residential buildings from the 1980s.
In 2015, the children's house "Casa Don Bosco" was built - architecturally based on the original building of the madhouse, which had been destroyed in bombings during World War II.
Marienplatz was listed as "Haupt Platz" around 1856, the Kaufingerstraße was called "Kaufinger Gasse".
The Second World War also brought a decisive change in the heart of Munich.
The Allied bombs tore many holes into the city centre in December 1944.
A large one remained until today - at Marienhof.
The English Institute, small business houses and a medieval tomb chapel once stood at the Marienhof, where the preliminary work is being done these days and the ground-breaking ceremony for the second S-Bahn main line takes place on 5 April 2017.
With the slider, the old Munich map can be compared to the aerial image of today - and fill the hole at the Marienhof.
Citizens' Rights Group publishes travel warning for Missouri
The National Association for the Promotion of Colored People has issued a warning to colored people who travel to Missouri due to the discriminatory policies and racist attacks of the state.
"The NAACP Travel Advisory for the State of Missouri, which is scheduled to enter into force by August 28, 2017, calls on African-American travelers, visitors and Missourians to pay special attention when travelling through the state and to exercise extreme caution, as a number of questionable racial-based incidents have recently occurred throughout the state and are noted here," the Group's opinion says.
A recently passed Missouri law that makes it harder for people to win discrimination lawsuits, as well as state law enforcement agencies that disproportionately target minorities, prompted the group to issue the travel warning, the NAACP said.
"They have violations of the civil rights that happen to people.
They are stopped for their skin color, they are beaten up or killed," said Missouri NAACP President Rod Chapel, the Kansas City Star.
"We hear complaints at such a frequency that we have not yet heard."
It is the first such warning issued by the organization for a state in the United States.
The group cited incidents such as racist offenses against black students at the University of Missouri and the death of Tory Sanders, 28, a black man from Tennessee.
Sanders died in questionable circumstances at the beginning of the year after he had no more petrol while traveling the state and was taken into custody by Missouri police without being accused of a crime.
The Council also refers to a recent report by the Missouri Attorney General's Office, which shows that black drivers in the state are stopped 75 percent more frequently than whites.
"The recommendation is that people are aware and inform their families, friends and employees about what could happen in Missouri," said Chapel.
"People must be ready to bring bail money or let relatives know they're traveling through the state."
Missouri recorded 100 hate crimes in 2015, according to the latest figures from the FBI's hate crime reporting program, which ranked the state 16th in terms of the number of such injuries.
The travel warning is also a response to a new Missouri law that would make it harder to sue a company for housing or employment discrimination.
Previously, the American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) had issued travel warnings for Texas and Arizona after states passed immigration laws requiring local law enforcement agencies to arrest people for immigration violations, which, according to ACLU, will contribute to further racial profiling.
Travel warnings are usually issued by the State Department for other countries, but recently interest groups have used the measure in response to certain laws and trends within the US.
