Is nothing sacred anymore?
Now the White House of Trump takes up the Statue of Liberty
The safest sign of a regime change is when they begin to attack the statues.
The Americans value this as much as any other - hence the carefully staged overthrow of Saddam Hussein on Firdos Square in Baghdad in 2003.
Stephen Miller, one of the key ideologists of the Trump regime, certainly knew what he was doing when he took with him a symbolic axe in a heated dispute with Jim Acosta of CNN about the President's proposals to drastically restrict legal immigration to the Statue of Liberty.
To remain fair, Miller did not attack the statue himself.
A horde of boat owners and Liberty impersonators would have lynched him if he had.
But he attacked their meaning, and in particular the meaning attributed to it when the famous poem by Emma Lazarus was added to its base in 1903, 17 years after the completion of the monument.
When Miller insulted Acosta, "I don't want to go into a whole thing about history here, but the Statue of Liberty is ... a symbol of American freedom that illuminates the world.
The poem to which you refer, which was later added and is not part of the original Statue of Liberty."
Miller's factually correct, but as he put it himself, it's not really about history.
It's about the contemporary response to the stirring words of Lazarus, the only ones in which a state not only invites some old immigrants, but the poorest of the poor: "Your tiredness, your poor, / your distressed masses who yearn to breathe freely, / the miserable apostasy of your rich coasts."
There was never a time when the "elder waste" could be seen better on our screens.
Miller did not engage in literary criticism - he made it clear that these people are not welcome in Trump's US.
This conflict over the importance of a statue is part of a broader political and cultural debate: it is indeed a conflict over the importance of America.
Lazarus - and her friends who fought to place their words at the base after her death - knew very well that they were carrying out a highly political act.
The sculpture was intended to show the connections between French and American Republicanism by depicting the female embodiment of freedom in a worn-out classical pictorial representation.
Lazarus changed this meaning: In her poem, the female figure is no longer abstract - she has received a voice.
And she gives herself a very different name: Mother of the Exiles.
The connection of the poem with the image is a brilliant feminist coup and a devastating attack on American nativity.
And just as Lazarus changed the meaning of the statue, the people from the right wing wanted to change it back for a long time.
The great cryneck Rush Limbaugh, a kind of John the Baptist for the coming of Trump, argued in 2010 that the Statue of Liberty was not inviting anyone, but rather an early neoconservative, bringing the American flame into the nightly world: "Lady Liberty is moving forward.
It is said to carry the torch of freedom from the United States to the rest of the world.
The torch should not light the way to the United States."
It's quite unusual that Limbaugh came across something here.
The significance of the statue is entirely a question of the point of view of perception.
The great imaginative act of Lazarus was to see her as she was seen by the exhausted, miserable, but hopeful people after long and often terrible journeys on the decks of ships.
In the truest sense, it is about seeing the world from the perspective of people seeking refuge and a chance to improve their lives.
Their statue speaks to them the words of hope and welcome they must hear.
And that, of course, is not the perspective that Miller and Trump would ever like to acknowledge.
Their torch shall not illuminate the way, but shall kindle the hatred which is their only source of power.
