New results of the Swedish Asylum Age Assessment Tests published
The recent results of tests for asylum seekers in Sweden, which have been subjected to a new method of medical assessment of their age, show that more than 80 percent of those tested are older than 18 years, but not everyone believes in the accuracy of these results.
The Swedish Forensic Medicine Authority (Rättsmedicinalverket) has started carrying out the tests last year.
During the asylum procedure, they are to make the assessment of age more precise after the Swedish Migration Authority (Migrationsverket) was criticised for errors in assessing the correct age of some refugees who were minors.
To date, Migrationsverket has sent 6,880 cases to be tested and the Forensic Medicine Agency has now published the results of a total of 2,481 tests from mid-March to 31 July 2017.
Eighty percent (2002) were judged as 18 or older, while in another 25 cases the Forensic Medicine Agency judged that the person was "possibly 18 years or older".
In 432 cases, the conclusion was that the person is "possibly under 18 years of age".
The tests are only carried out in cases where the age of the person is questioned.
According to Johan Göransson of the Forensic Medicine Agency, the results have been consistent over the past months.
"We don't see a big difference in the statistics of the past months, the numbers are pretty constant," he said to The Local magazine.
The high proportion of cases in which the person was assessed as over 18 years does not necessarily mean that the asylum seeker lied about his age.
In May, the agency published the results of 581 tests, saying that there were 442 cases that "proposed that the person under investigation be 18 years or older".
When the newspaper Svenska Dagbladet examined the 581 published results, she noted that in 243 of these cases the person had openly said that she would be 18 years old this year.
The method of medical age assessment, in which x-rays of wisdom teeth and MRI recordings of knee joints are made, which are then analyzed by dentists and radiologists, has also been criticized in some areas.
A skeptic is the endocrinologist Claude Marcus of the Karolinska Institute, whose work includes assessing the biological maturity of humans to see if they went through puberty sooner or later than usual.
"I had reason to think about it, and I don't think the type of measurement should be used.
To judge biological age in this way is very uncertain.
If we can't say it for sure, we shouldn't pretend we could," he told the Metro newspaper.
Göransson of the Forensic Medicine Agency, however, defended the accuracy of the tests: "In general, you can say that the risk of judging a child as an adult incorrectly is low.
The biggest risk is when the person is just under 18, in this case this is about 10 percent."
