How the financial rules of football affect Neymar's move to Paris
The rules aimed at preventing unhindered spending by European football clubs will not disturb Neymar's world record transfer from Spanish Barcelona to French Paris-Saint Germain.
Any consequences will still come for Paris Saint-Germain from UEFA, because the leading organization that oversees the European game has the power to ban teams from access to the prestigious Champions League tournament.
Financial fair-play rules launched by UEFA in 2011 mean that PSG will have to prove at some point that Neymar's transfer was financed without major losses.
Barcelona has paid 222 million euros (262 million dollars) to buy the Brazilian out of its contract, and Neymar will receive a salary that will amount to several ten million dollars a year.
Here are some of Neymar's financial aspects of moving to France.
PSG can certainly loosen the money so that Neymar signs and takes him to a galaxy of other stars, given the financing of the team by the energy-rich ruling family of Qatar.
Clubs are allowed to spend a lot of money on acquiring players, but have to counter with legitimate revenue sources that allow them to break-even point in their football-related business.
FFP was conceived by Michel Platini after his election as UEFA President in 2007.
The former French player believed that clubs that had incurred enormous debts in their quest for success effectively cheated and risked ruining themselves when banks or owners withdrew their support.
In 2011, FFP shifted from concentrating on the clubs' debt to monitoring their losses.
The change meant that the business model that Roman Abramovich originally used in Chelsea in 2003 - bought a club with potential and then invested heavily to improve the team and build a global brand - should become a tougher matter.
During the current three-year FFP assessment period, which runs until 2018, clubs can accept losses of EUR 30 million.
And even though Platini fell out of favor by the presidency in 2015, his UEFA successor Aleksander Ceferin continues to campaign to discourage excessive spending.
"FFP is certainly not dead and we will definitely strengthen the rules for the future," said Andrea Traverso, who is responsible for FFP at UEFA, to The Associated Press last week.
Although the PSG paid Neymar's buy-out clause in a lump sum, it can distribute the amount for accounting over the duration of its contract.
Neymar has signed a five-year contract, so that the transfer sum of EUR 44.4 million for the next five years can be shown in the financial statements.
The first wave of FFP sanctions in 2014 has hit the PSG with the heaviest sanctions along with Abu Dhabi, which is owned by Manchester City.
The PSG received a fine of 60 million euros (then 82 million dollars), which was later reduced to 20 million euros - and it was ordered that the team members for the 2014–15 Champions League remain limited to 21 players instead of the otherwise normal 25 players.
UEFA is looking for clubs that could try to outsmart their financial supervision by bloating their revenues through companies associated with the owners of a club.
While a Qatari company could sponsor the PSG if the value of sponsorship exceeded the standard market rates, UEFA would not let this be considered a legitimate income.
This is exactly what happened in 2014, when UEFA decided that the value of sponsoring the PSA was bloated by the Qatar Tourism Authority.
It was reported that part of the PSG payments to Neymar could come through payments from the World Cup organizing committee in Qatar in 2022.
But PSG and Qatar in 2022 have denied that Neymar will become World Cup ambassadors and such a maneuver could be easy to find for UEFA regulators.
The sanctions against PSG so far mean that UEFA will be even more attentive to any attempt to circumvent the rules.
UEFA had no preparatory talks with PSG about Neymar's transfer, said Thursday the people who are familiar with the situation.
They spoke to The Associated Press on condition of anonymity, as they were not authorized to discuss the PSG situation.
The latest published reports show that PSG generated a profit of more than 10 million euros in 2015/16 with a turnover of 542.4 million euros.
The accounts for the last financial year still have to be published.
PSG expects Neymar's arrival to be a blessing for sponsorship deals, merchandising and jersey sales.
The association expects sales to increase by at least 30 percent after the signing.
The Spanish league was clearly irritated to see one of the best footballers go, and they tried to prevent Neymar's departure by claiming that PSG would violate the FFP.
"It is a clear case of "financial doping" with the club and the state," said the president of the La Liga, Javier Tebas, the Spanish daily AS regarding Qatar's eventual ownership of PSG.
Arsenal manager Arsene Wenger, whose club is owned by an American sports tycoon, shares the reservations of La Liga against a state that finances a club.
"It's the consequence of ownership and that has completely changed the whole landscape of football over the last 15 years," said Wenger on Thursday.
"As soon as a country owns a club, anything is possible.
It will be very difficult to respect financial fair play because you can go different ways or have different interests if a country has such a big player to represent a country."
