The now broken colossus has been a part of the Larsen C shelf ice.
Ice shelf floats on the sea and is fed by large glaciers.
It thus continues to grow into the sea and breaks off regularly.
The Larsen C Ice Shelf is located south of South America almost at the tip of the Antarctic Peninsula.
North of this shelf ice, the balance of growth and breaking was disturbed a few years ago.
A complete shelf ice had disintegrated there, writes AWI researcher Daniela Jansen.
There is some reason to believe that the Larsen C shelf ice is also in danger, as the front edge has never retreated as far as it is currently.
In addition, the ice plate is under tension and can disintegrate if a piece breaks off at a key point.
The melting of shelf ice and iceberg does not increase sea level as they swim on the water and displace ice as much water as it results after melting itself.
However, the loss of the shelf ice causes the glaciers to flow directly into the sea and drain much faster than before.
This could possibly increase the sea level, but only to a small extent, writes the British Antarctic Observation Research Project (Midas).
According to AWI data, the Larsen C Ice Shelf is the fourth largest ice shelf in Antarctica with almost 50,000 square kilometres.
