Deutsche Bahn: Group tests "Comfort Check-in"
It is a moment that almost everyone has experienced before: you sit on the train and sleep without knowing anything.
Or you're absorbed in your work and you have a brilliant thought right now.
And then: pufff.
Comes the conductor and wakes you up uneasy or rips the passenger out of the middle of the workflow.
Ticket control.
But the times of interruptions are almost over.
Deutsche Bahn is currently testing the schaffnerlost ticket control.
You simply confirm by cell phone that you take your place and thus devalue the ticket.
Currently, a test operation is running on two routes.
"When the offer arrives, we extend it.
It is expected to be available on many other long-distance routes in Germany at the beginning of next year," said a railway spokesman.
"Comfort Check-in" is the name of the train's ticket depreciation without a conductor.
In order to be able to use these, however, some requirements must be met: You need a smartphone or a tablet.
And you have to have booked an online ticket - what most passengers already do.
You must also have bought it via the app of the train, the DB Navigator, which is the most convenient way to book a ticket anyway.
And last but not least, you need a seat reservation.
Because the "comfort check-in" works like this: you get on the train, call up your ticket under "My tickets".
A button for electronic devaluation will then appear in the test customers.
The train attendants receive a message on their mobile devices that Passenger X is on the train and has taken the booked seat Y.
When the train attendant checks the ticket, he knows that a passenger is sitting there with an already devalued online ticket.
So you can go back to sleep, work on, keep silent.
The "check-in" has two advantages: one for the customer, one for the train - which in turn should benefit passengers.
"Anyone who wants to travel relaxed without ticket control through our train attendants, simply check in in the DB Navigator itself.
This allows passengers to make their travel time more personal on the train," says Michael Peterson, Marketing Board member of DB Fernverkehr.
Second plus: "And our employees have more time than today to respond to individual customer needs".
Anyone who often travels by train knows that, in addition to delays and missed trains, ticket checks are one of the biggest troubles.
Because you often have yourself, but in any case one of the fellow travellers does not have all the documents you need to devalue online tickets.
Either the credit card or the identity card or any other document you have to present.
The result is endless discussions between train attendants and passengers, which leads to bad mood in the compartment or large room and delays in controlling your own ticket and ultimately takes the time for the conductor to take care of other concerns.
Only a small number of test customers can still use the new service.
And only on the connections ICE 915 Dortmund-Stuttgart and ICE 912 Stuttgart-Essen.
Further train numbers on the same route are not yet activated.
How did an activist get to learn the answer to the question, "What Streets?"
On 9 August 2014, Brittany Ferrell was shaken to its core.
Just one day after she arrived in New York City, the one born in St. Louis sat on the bed of an airbnb apartment she rented and scrolled through Facebook on her phone.
She stumbled across a post from someone from high school.
"The police just killed an 18-year-old child, and it's still on the street," they said.
Confused, as no one else had posted the information on their feed, she closed Facebook and opened Twitter.
A user with the handle @TheePharoah was constantly retweeted on their timeline.
The rapper from the St. Louis area was about to tweet the death of Michael Brown, an unarmed black 18-year-old killed by a white police officer in Ferguson, Mo., live.
He posted a picture of Brown's lifeless body stretched out on the street and would stay there for four hours.
"That's wild," Ferrell thought to himself.
But death was nothing new to her and her community.
She dropped off her phone to return later that evening to tweets about people on the Canfield drive.
There were photos of the police tape and people screaming, and of a man who claimed to be Brown's father carrying a sign saying, "Ferguson's police just killed my unarmed son!"
She watched a live feed where a police officer stood in front of a group of protesters with a barking dog.
In another video, she said, another police officer released his rifle and shouted, "I will kill you... animals all."
"This is not common," Ferrell recalled her statement.
"That's not the kind of murder we've gotten used to and that we can call typical."
At that moment, I felt chills.
I was angry and cried."
She booked a return flight and went home the next day.
After landing at 11 p.m., she picked up her 6-year-old daughter from her father's house and decided that the two would go to Ferguson the next morning.
What happened to Ferrell and Ferguson in the following three years is the subject of a new documentary film, "Whos Streets?", in the cinemas from the 11th century onwards.
It is a story of survival and protest, love and loss, strength and resilience, which consists of the view of the people who live in the community and have filled the streets to demand answers.
When Ferrell went to Ferguson with her daughter, who wore a flower dress and a matching crown, they discussed a conversation that they had "about the black experience and the black state" countless times before this morning.
"You remember how I taught you when black people have to fight for what they believe in?" she remembered what she said.
"We're going to Ferguson now because the police killed an 18-year-old boy and that wasn't right.
I couldn't take her," Ferrell said later.
"What happened today is a highlight of what happened in the past.
She needs to know and see it and be raised in it.
It must be well developed, not only activism and organization, but also know the different layers of black experience and the black constitution, and what we need to do to become free, to free ourselves.
Even if I am lucky enough to give her an experience in which she personally does not experience any blatant racism, she is no different than the next black woman child.
I feel like I would do her a bad service to keep her away from it."
The first stop when they arrived at Ferguson was on South Florissant Road, a place opposite the police department that became a camp area when the activists were waiting for Officer Darren Wilson's possible non-acclamation.
There Ferrell and her daughter joined a local business owner who made lunch.
They prepared bags and helped pass them on to protesters.
Slowly a new kind of activism for Ferrell began to take shape.
"My activism has changed completely after 9 August," she said, noting that as a student at the University of Missouri-St. Louis, she was president of the Minority Student Nurses Association and focused on eating justice and health inequalities in black communities.
"I had no experience in organizing.
It's all come."
Weeks later, Ferrell met Sabaah Folayan, one of the film's co-directors, during an evening demonstration.
Folayan said she and her cameraman Lucas Alvarado-Farrar just wanted to "document" what happened.
One question came to Ferrell's mind: "Do you want to document or try to find a story that you can take advantage of?"
This skepticism was nurtured by countless cases of people, often by whites - in a community that benefited from their pain and resilience.
As Folayan recently stated in an interview, "We had heard that people born and raised in Ferguson did not center their voices and we wanted to do it differently."
Folayan had already collaborated with former co-director Damon Davis, an artist from the field known for his activism around death row inmates.
His engagement brought Ferrell closer to the project, along with six other locals, followed the team of "Whos Streets?" in the years after Brown's shooting.
"This documentary is not someone who speaks for us or speaks to us. We talk," Davis said.
"That was the main thing for me, how these people are represented, because that's how I'm going to be represented."
The goal was not to focus on Ferrell's experience - to show that the movement "is not a Messiah leader, but a community that comes together," said Folayan - she proved to be the most open participant in the film.
As a result, documents from "Whos Streets?" show surprisingly personal aspects of Ferrell's life as she falls in love and marries her wife.
"I felt like naked," said Ferrell, laughing when she saw the finished product for the first time.
"But I understand that there must be some vulnerability in this work and in the humanization of black people."
In addition, Ferrell's story repeats the role of black gay women in the wider Black Lives Matter movement.
Two of the three founders of the movement, who coined the film "BlacklivesMatter" in social media after the murder of black teenager Trayvon Martin in 2012, identify themselves as gay.
"Black, gay women in executive positions have worn the movement as a whole," said Ferrell, "and therefore we are constantly fighting on different fronts.
Black, gay women must bear the brunt of everything."
Folayan agreed to note that "the movement is really being maintained by black women and many black women".
However, she insists that "this is not an affirmative type of action", in which Ferrell was chosen as the heart of the film due to her identity.
"She was the person who stirred up this energy," she said.
"It's no coincidence, even though she was on the front line, because there's so much at stake in a life at these intersections as a black, gay woman.
You can feel their energy through the screen."
Meanwhile, the news cameras in Ferguson have long disappeared, but the racial links between the community and the police continue to exist.
Ferrell is on parole for 21⁄2 years because of blocking a highway at a demonstration.
She describes the socio-political atmosphere of the area she calls her home: "a chaos".
Nevertheless, she clings to a song and she feels committed to this memory since she took to the streets in Ferguson three years ago.
"It is our duty to fight for our freedom.
It is our duty to win.
We must love and support each other.
We have nothing to lose - except our chains."
