A fitting similarity: artist creates portraits with Chelsea Manning's DNA
In the middle of the room of the Fridman Gallery in New York there are many faces - white, black and brown, almost imperceptibly alike - hanging on cables from the ceiling.
The 30 portraits were created by the artist Heather Dewey-Hagborg from cheek swabs and haircuts sent to her by Chelsea Manning.
Manning sent the clippings from Fort Leavenworth prison, where the former intelligence analyst served a 35-year prison term after making classified diplomatic reports public through the WikiLeaks website.
The new exhibition, which opened on 2 August, is called A Becoming Resemblance (A fitting similarity).
It is the product of two years of correspondence between Dewey-Hagborg, whose discipline combined her expertise in technology, computer science, and art, and Manning, a transwoman and pioneering dissident whose condemnation was converted by Barack Obama when he had only three days in office.
Dewey-Hagborg has created a sharp, though somewhat intellectual, commentary not only on the formability of DNA data - the many ways in which they can be interpreted and the inherent determinism of these interpretations - but also on identity through the algorithmic analysis of DNA extracted from Manning and created from the 30 portraits as someone with these genomic data could look.
Manning, who was born Bradley Edward but has been openly talking about identifying as a woman since her puberty, was convicted of 20 charges in 2013, including six violations of the spy law, computer fraud, and theft.
Her image was suppressed by the prison, so much so that there was only one photo - a grainy, black-and-white selfie in which Manning was visibly uncomfortable sitting in a driver's seat and wearing a platinum-blonde wig - to which she was associated.
In 2015, Dewey-Hagborg just came from the great success of her 2012 project 'Stranger Visions'.
In it, the artist produced portraits of strangers from forensic artifacts such as cigarette butts and chewing gum by extracting DNA from the garbage to create a picture of what these people might look like.
That was the time she received an e-mail from a newspaper magazine.
"They conducted an interview with Chelsea Manning while she was in prison, and they wanted a kind of portrait to accompany this article," Dewey-Hagborg explained at a press preview of the new exhibition.
And she couldn't visit at that time and she couldn't be photographed, so you made contact with Chelsea and asked her if she wanted to make a DNA portrait.
The artist and her imprisoned muse became unequal pen pals who exchanged several letters over the course of two years.
They even created a comic book "Suppressed Images", illustrated by Shoili Kanungo, which foresaw a future in which President Chelsea's judgment would be transformed and she would be able to see the exhibition in person.
That Obama would actually demand Manning's release after seven brutal years in a military prison in Kansas just a few days after the book was published was a welcome kind of happy encounter.
