The advertising costs of the White House cost the taxpayer thousands
The White House's decision to fly a marine helicopter to the South Lawn for an event highlighting American manufacturing last month costs taxpayers up to $24,000, according to military figures left to TIME magazine.
The green-white Sikorsky VH-3D, known as Marine One, when the President is on board, was the heart of the July 17 event at the White House with American construction programs.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence and White House senior officials took a tour of products from all 50 states.
The Connecticut-made helicopter was exhibited alongside a Maine yacht, a Wisconsin fire truck, and a Mississippi forklift.
The White House military office demanded the presence of the helicopter in a fragmentary order or FRAGO, barely 36 hours before the helicopter landed on the South Lawn, according to the records of the Marine Helicopter Squadron One (HMX-1), the unit responsible for operating the helicopter.
"I just wanted you to be aware of this, because it is such an unusual event with high visibility," wrote the commander of HMX-1 on the eve of the event to his superior, the deputy naval commander for aviation.
The news indicated that the helicopter arrived at the South Lawn at around 7 a.m. on 17 July for the event at 3 p.m., and remained until the lawn was cleared between 6:00 and 9:00 p.m. that evening.
The note adds that if the departure from the White House was delayed, due to the limitation of duty hours, a second crew would be required for the return flight.
The original flight crew was with the helicopter during the event, while the unit's safety personnel remained on the ground with the aircraft during the time.
It was not clear from the records made available to TIME whether a second flight crew member was ultimately required.
The Hatch Act prohibits federal employees from using state property for political purposes.
Records indicate that HMX-1 asked if the event could violate the determination.
"One question we asked was whether it was a violation of the Hatch Act and we were informed that this was not the case," the commander wrote.
"Sounds like you're locked," replied the deputy commander.
The "Made in America" event was designated by the White House as an official event and would not have been covered by the Hatch Act.
But official events also have political overtones.
At the event, the president gave an impetus to the reform of the health reform that was underway in the Senate, and he propagated the efforts to curb government regulations.
The use of the aircraft known as Marine One or Air Force One for politically beneficial purposes is hardly a new phenomenon.
Presidents are obliged to use them for the journey.
But demanding their use only for a photo surgery is unusual.
Trump conducted an investigation in February when the presidential plane provided taxi services against the backdrop of its first campaign rally in Melbourne, Florida, and its Twitter account is full of reports complaining about the use of the presidential aircraft by its predecessor.
"The White House is thrilled with the show "Made In America" - showing products from all 50 states produced by American workers using American materials," said the White House's deputy press secretary, Lindsay Walters.
HMX-1 crews frequently conduct training flights in the Washington area and in the South Lawn to drop the U.S. president at the White House with precise centimeter sets.
When Trump was at the G20 summit in Germany in early July, HMX-1 conducted 58 exercise landings at the White House.
The flight for the "Made in America" event counted in the training needs of the flight crew for the month, said one official.
Helicopter units flew an additional 11 hours that day for "non-presidency support missions".
The White House said that taxpayers took over the burden for none of the other props presented at the event.
A spokesman for Sikorsky said the company had not been involved in exhibiting the helicopter on the South Lawn.
HMX-1 does not maintain budget records for presidential flights, and it is difficult to determine the exact cost of the event.
However, according to U.S. Department of Defense hourly rates for the 2017 financial year, the DoD refund rate for the VH-3D is USD 24,380 per flight hour.
Records of the unit record the flight time of the aircraft as 30 minutes from the Marine Corps Air Facility's home base in Quantico, Virginia.
The White House argues that the actual cost of operating the helicopter is far below this rate.
"Setting the cost of taxpayers on the basis of estimates of reimbursement rates is highly misleading," said Walters.
"These estimates include staff, maintenance and many other hidden costs included in the annual funds."
According to a 2015 RAND study, the reimbursement rates for DoD do not include personnel costs, but take into account the costs of fuel, maintenance and contract conclusion.
At the time, the former White House press officer, Sean Spicer, defended the use of the helicopter for the event.
"The idea this week is to present things that are made in America," Spicer said.
"And I know that Sikorsky and the state of Connecticut are very proud that they contribute to our national security, and I assume that hundreds, if not thousands, of people depend on it.
And I think, like most Americans, we are all proud of the helicopter and other military equipment for which so many Americans have worked tirelessly.
It is, of course, appropriate to emphasize this."
It was not clear whether Trump interacted with the helicopter as he entered his tour of the South Lawn for the event, but he sat down in the driver's seat of a fire engine car.
In the White House, Trump spoke to representatives of Sikorsky and joked with the media about his own fleet of company products.
"I know Sikorsky very well," said the President, "I have three of them."
