GMB concern about investment in the McVitie factory in Glasgow
A union wants to verify the long-term commitment to production at its Glasgow plant with managers of the biscuit manufacturer McVitie.
GMB Scotland said the company had kept silent about the future of investment at the Tollcross site.
More than 500 employees work at the plant, which produces Hobnobs and Rich Tea biscuits alongside other products.
McVities owner Pladis said he has invested more than £5 million in recent years.
He added that employees and trade union representatives would be "the first to experience" if their activities changed.
In a letter to the company's branch manager, GMB Scotland urged McVitie's to "explain concerns that funding for the modernization of production lines is not being pushed forward".
GMB senior organizer Drew Duffy said, "The fact that we cannot gain clarity from the general site manager about the business needs and investment plans for the future of Tollcross deeply affects our members.
Generations of families have worked here and the workforce is heavily concentrated on the local community and the Greater Glasgow area, an important pillar for decent employment in an area with high unemployment and social disadvantage.
Therefore, from the perspective of jobs, wages and prosperity, and against the background of Brexit, the rising cost of living and the chronic decline in production, the eastern end of Glasgow urgently needs a flourishing production presence at McVitie".
A spokesperson for Pladis said: "Tollcross's branch manager received a letter from GMB Scotland only yesterday, and the company will respond directly as we appreciate the continued commitment of employees and union representatives.
We had a regular meeting with employees and GMB representatives at Tollcross two months ago, during which some questions were openly discussed.
We discussed with the employees that, like all companies operating in an extremely competitive and uncertain economic climate, we are constantly reviewing our business - and this applies to all our business units and locations - in order to remain competitive.
She added: "In recent years, we have invested more than £5 million in our Tollcross location, especially in production lines and operational improvements.
We fully recognise the heritage of Tollcross as a production site. Should our operations at the site change, the employees and their union representatives will be the first to know."
Did the PSG warn Barcelona about Neymar three years ago?
The side of La Liga may regret their interest in Marco Trätti
Paris Saint-Germain will not slacken in her pursuit of Neymar after making an offer of £ 189 million to trigger his release clause, but did they warn Barcelona three years ago before the world record robbery?
The sensational approach has fueled the transfer window in the summer, as the Ligue 1 club is ready to break the world record by more than double the previous brand, with Paul Pogba returning to Manchester United last season for £89 million.
After finishing, Neymar becomes the most expensive player in the world and the world’s highest-paid professional athlete. PSG offers wages of more than GBP 500,000 per week.
