Interview: "Domspatzen report relieves Pope brother Georg Ratzinger"
The Regensburg Domspatzen report on the abuse cases relieves Pope brother Georg Ratzinger.
That's what author and historian Michael Hesemann means.
The final report on the abuse scandal at the Regensburg Cathedral Spatzen continues to provide discussion.
Christian Weisnder, spokesman for the Reform Movement "Wir sind Kirche", said after publication to the German Press Agency that he expected an apology from the former Bishop of Regensburg and today's Cardinal Gerhard Ludwig Müller as well as from Domkapellmeister Georg Ratzinger, 93-year-old brother of the emeritus Pope Benedict XVI.
It would greatly serve the reputation of the Catholic Church if Müller and Ratzinger expressed their deep regret at their own omissions or at the time their false assessment of the processes.
The Vatican newspaper "Osservatore Romano", on the other hand, criticized the fact that reporting on violence in the cathedral spats was measured with "two measures".
With regard to the attacks in Regensburg, no one doubts that these are "infamous and shameful acts" which must be punished and prevented in the future; however, the "degree of media manipulation" is striking, according to author Lucetta Scaraffia, historian and member of the national Italian Bioethics Committee.
"The habit of calling the Catholic Church the source of all evil is already part of everyday experience and prepares public opinion to consider it normal," Scaraffia writes.
Princess Gloria von Thurn and Taxis also said in an interview with Bayerischer Rundfunk: "You like to go to the church and that's a food you've found."
She also pointed out that in her youth "clashes were a normal educational means" "to cope with naughty children, as I was one."
She felt it unfair to apply today’s standards to earlier decades, for the world had changed.
In connection with the reports on abuse cases, Pope brother Georg Ratzinger often also appeared.
Author and historian Michael Hesemann, who co-authored the memory book "My Brother the Pope" with Ratzinger (translated into 12 languages), is completely wrong.
"I have to protect Georg Ratzinger," says Hesemann, "because all this had nothing to do with him," he evaluates the results of the final report.
What exactly does the 440-page report by the lawyer Ulrich Weber, commissioned by the Bishopric of Regensburg with the Enlightenment, say?
A total of 547 Regensburg cathedral spats were sexually abused between 1945 and the early 1990s "with high plausibility" victims of assaults, 67 cathedral spats.
The final report says about Georg Ratzinger, who worked in Regensburg from 1964 to 1994: "In summary, it can be stated that Domkapellmeister R. used forms of physical and psychological violence in many cases.
Especially with high emotionality, the punishment for the students could also be more severe.
Nevertheless, unlike many other accused, it is striking that many victims appreciated the general humanity of R. and therefore, in many cases, despite violence, even associate positive memories with him".
In the interview, Hesemann explains why he believes that the final report on the abuse scandal at the Regensburg cathedral spats relieves Georg Ratzinger.
Mr. Hesemann, the 440-page report on the "accidents of violence against victims at the Regensburg Cathedral Spatzen" gives a contradictory picture of Domkapellmeister Georg Ratzinger.
On the one hand, many students highlight his "humanity".
On the other hand, he also appears as a choleric and perfectionist, who often became tangible when a cathedral spat did not deliver top performance musically.
How do you, as his biographer, rate this final report?
Michael Hesemann: If you take the trouble and read the entire 440-page report from the front to the back, you have to ask yourself why the name Georg Ratzinger even occurs in it.
Only eight pages are dedicated to him and he is clearly acquitted of any suspicion of complicity or co-intelligence in the terrible cases of sexual abuse.
The excesses of violence at preschool also occurred outside his sphere of influence.
One can at best accuse him of having learned of it too late or of not taking the first hints seriously enough.
The Domspatzengymnasium, on which he was active, was perceived by virtually all respondents as - so literally - "salvation", "heaven" and "better world".
Thus, the vast majority of his students Georg Ratzinger also presents a very excellent testimony, describing him as "warm", "popular", "sincere", "competent" and "comprehensive", as an extremely good-natured teacher who regularly provided the boys with cakes, biscuits and sweets and was "always surrounded by grapes from children".
Only a minority complains about its perfectionism and its high emotionality, which also led to anger outbreaks.
The fact that he not only banged with chairs and threw the keyring on the floor, but also spread slaps and pulled too cheeky boys by the hair or ears, he himself admitted years ago, deeply regrets and apologizes for it.
However, in order to save his honor, it must be said that such educational methods were widespread in the period in question, the 1960s and 1970s, both among parents and teachers.
Do you also know such methods of punishment?
Of course, I think each of us who was born before 1968.
I, too, have experienced this in a secular school, a state high school.
Compared to what this report is actually about, namely the appalling sexual abuse and the excesses of violence in preschool, these are, of course, trivial.
Then one wonders whether it is not more about his fame and his role as brother of Benedict XVI that many media have just jumped at him.
Many who have never understood him are still busy working on the Bavarian Pope.
But the truth is: the report relieves Georg Ratzinger in every way!
In the media, much has been reported in connection with the report on the subject of abuse at the Regensburg Cathedral Spatzen.
Is Georg Ratzinger also charged with any involvement or co-ordination in sexual abuse in the final report?
Michael Hesemann: Clearly no.
Not one of the 67 victims of sexual assault claims to have committed himself to the Domkapellmeister.
Not even the parents were initiated.
"I never dared to talk to my father or my mother about it," one of the people affected said on behalf of the others, "It was all very embarrassing to me."
The real problem in investigating sexual abuse was, and is, that most victims are silent out of shame.
If they did not even entrust themselves to parents and siblings, then certainly not to a choir director, who would have been a colleague of the perpetrators in a professional sense.
How do the Domspatzen students assess Ratzinger's role in the cases of abuse?
Michael Hesemann: A student questioned put it this way: "With regard to sexual abuse ... I don't see ... any case in which he (Georg Ratzinger) of all people would have had timely insights and could have stopped the respective perpetrator.
I think it ... is also really absurd to assume that he of all people ... boys have opened up more forceful or clearer or rather than to their parents, boarding school leaders, teachers of trust, etc.
Talking to him about sex is unthinkable."
Thus, the report comes to the very clear conclusion: "The fact that the students concerned and/or their environment were entrusted to him in advance could not be confirmed in the course of the study".
As far as sexual abuse is concerned, Georg Ratzinger must therefore be acquitted of any complicity.
Nor can he be accused of not having prevented him or brought him to justice.
There is therefore no reason to associate his good name with these disgusting crimes, as has unfortunately happened in some cases.
In the media there was much to read about "gewaltexzessen" at the Regensburg Cathedral Spatzen.
The former Domkapellmeister Georg Ratzinger is accused in the report "Looking the Way".
Does he have to live with this accusation?
Michael Hesemann: That's the big problem that everything in the coverage was mixed and mixed up into a huge melange of sexual abuse and excesses of violence and somewhere, in the middle of it, Georg Ratzinger.
But that, in turn, is an abuse of the report.
There is a clean separation: between the preschool and the Gymnasium der Domspatzen, between sexual abuse and excesses of violence and, let's say, other accusations.
In addition, the report deals with incidents from the period since 1945, i.e. also from four decades, in which Georg Ratzinger was not choir director of the cathedral spats.
All the terrible beating pedagogy, the cases in which boys were harassed and maltreated by sadist teachers and suffered horribly from it, all occurred at the preschool in Etterzhausen and Pielenhofen, where truly scandalous conditions must have prevailed.
But Domkapellmeister Georg Ratzinger had nothing to do with them, because he didn't get to see the boys until they were already at the Dompatzengymnasium.
As most of the Witnesses stress, the subject of preschool was taboo.
One was only happy to have escaped it and enjoyed so much better treatment and for many even "paradisaic" conditions.
What was different at the Domspatzengymnasium?
Michael Hesemann: There was discipline, but no sadistic violence.
And this also applies to Georg Ratzinger, in which the report concludes that "many victims appreciated the general humanity of R. and therefore in many cases, despite violence, even combine positive memories with him".
At most, this leaves the accusation of looking away.
However, despite all the efforts, the report could only define two periods during which it was reported about preschool conditions.
The first time in 1970/71, when he was beginning to establish himself and from the events at a school where he was not active and responsible (so the witness did not want to hear anything), and then again around 1993.
Has Georg Ratzinger consistently closed his ears before the conditions?
Michael Hesemann: No, because as early as 1989 he wrote a letter to the director of the Cathedral Spatzen High School, which the report even reproduces.
In this, he points out to him that "the beating sentence continues to be practised in preschool".
In view of the danger of negative press releases, he recommended urgent action.
This was, of course, at a time when legal clarity existed, when beating sentences were long forbidden in Bavaria.
Before that, they occurred in a legal grey area, as each of us probably still knows.
It was also difficult for him to estimate where those affected might have been exaggerated or dramatized and where the permissible limit had really been exceeded.
But you can't say he'd always looked away.
That's just not true.
It was not until 1980 that the beating penalty at schools was officially abolished in Bavaria.
Princess Gloria of Thurn and Taxis claimed that it was unfair to apply today’s educational standards to those days.
How do you see that?
Michael Hesemann: We historians are talking about the "fall trick of anachronism", i.e. the danger of judging past by today's moral standards.
The princess is right about that.
But of course this does not apply to sexual abuse, which at all times was abominable and also not to what was committed in preschool in the face of adversity and violence against innocent children's souls, that goes far beyond what was then usual.
It's all awful and I'm glad it's finally being reworked.
But at the same time I have to protect Georg Ratzinger, because all this had nothing to do with him.
His means of disciplining and punishing, i.e. slapping and pulling at the hair and ears, were widespread in the 1970s.
When physical punishment was then banned, he also strictly adhered to it.
What picture of his time in Regensburg has Georg Ratzinger reproduced in the conversations with you for the book "My brother the Pope"?
Did the subject of beatings also come up?
Michael Hesemann: Well, the book is about the life of his brother Joseph, Pope Benedict XVI, from his perspective, where the cathedral spats only played a supporting role.
Nevertheless, I am by no means hiding that he had a strict regiment there.
But this must also be said: without this perfectionism, without the demand for unconditional discipline, it would hardly have been possible for him to form a world-class institution out of Regensburg Cathedral Spatzen, which was until then more known nationally, true cultural ambassadors of Europe and its musical tradition, who went on tour twice in the USA (1983 and 1987) and Japan (1988 and 1991).
With biscuits and sweets alone, you don't make a big singer out of unruly boys and stand before every success, no matter in which field, but always discipline, passion and self-overcome.
What kind of person did you see Georg Ratzinger talking about her book?
Michael Hesemann: Through my work on the book and beyond, I really got to know Georg Ratzinger very well and experienced it again and again as a wonderful, humorous, profound, deeply believing and hearty person, of whom one cannot imagine that he could even do something to a fly.
I regularly get to know how many former cathedral spats still today, 23 years after his retirement, regularly keep in touch with him, visit him, read to him - he is almost blind - and treat him as a member of her family.
So those who still do not forgive him that he was once strict with them are clearly in the minority.
Most of the cathedral spats today are grateful to him for enriching their lives and bringing them closer to the world of music.
And that he was always a good fatherly teacher - a strict father, certainly, that may be - but nevertheless also a lovable respect person, to whom they still look up today and to whom they almost adore.
And please, once again quite clearly, all that is accused of him are educational methods that were common at the time.
We can be glad that we have overcome this time long ago.
But it is most unjust to make a man a media scapegoat just because he is prominent and has an even more prominent brother.
There's the evil intent behind it all too obvious.
Because the report that has just been published relieves him.
Now the decency would command, a 93-year-old man, who has earned great merit and without the outside Bavaria and perhaps still Germany probably no one would know the Regensburg cathedral spats, to finally leave in peace.
